enbury Manor, Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Glassenbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Glassenbury, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Winchett Hall, Goudhurst, Kent, England":"Goudhurst, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1350–1441":"1350–1441","1353–Female":"1353–Deceased","1376–1441":"1376–1441","1350–1440":"1350–1440","1330–1380":"1330–1380","1334–Female":"1334–Deceased","1334":"1334","1376":"1376","1441":"1441","1353":"1353","1330":"1330","1440":"1440","1350":"1350","about 1376":"about 1376","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","Glassenbury Manor, Cranbrook, Kent, England":"Cranbrook, Kent, England","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Glassenbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Glassenbury, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Winchett Hall, Goudhurst, Kent, England":"Goudhurst, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Robertes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the personal name   Robert  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is also occasionally borne by Jews, presumably as an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) Jewish surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Robert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Marcel, Gilles, Normand, Armand, Lucien, Pierre, Emile, Michel, Edouard, Gaston, Yves.","French, Walloon, English, German, Dutch, Flemish, and Breton (of French origin); Hungarian (<b>Róbert</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Ro(d)bert</i> (Middle English <i>Robert</i>, Old French <i>Ro(d)bert</i>), composed of the elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame, renown’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This is found occasionally in Anglo-Saxon England before the Conquest, but in the main it was introduced into England by the Normans and quickly became popular among all classes of society. Pet forms and diminutives are found from an early date,   Robin   being particularly common. Compare   Robair  ,   Robar  ,   Robare  , and   Rober  .","In some cases also an Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Robers","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Roberds","meanings":["English: variant of   Roberts  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Robards","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Roberts  ."]},{"name":"Robarts","meanings":["English (Bedfordshire and Hertfortshire): variant of   Roberts  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Robertes was born in 1350, in Cranbrook, Kent, England, his father, Sir Willi